  journal      = apj,
  doi          = {10.3847/1538-4357/ac0625},
  eprinttype   = arxiv,
  eprint       = {2102.09707},
  eprintClass  = {astro-ph.CO},
  abstract     = {We propose a novel method to reconstruct
                  high-resolution three-dimensional mass maps using
                  data from photometric weak-lensing surveys. We apply
                  an adaptive LASSO algorithm to perform a
                  sparsity-based reconstruction on the assumption that
                  the underlying cosmic density field is represented
                  by a sum of Navarro--Frenk--White halos. We generate
                  realistic mock galaxy shear catalogs by considering
                  the shear distortions from isolated halos for the
                  configurations matched to the Subaru Hyper
                  Suprime-Cam Survey with its photometric redshift
                  estimates. We show that the adaptive method
                  significantly reduces line-of-sight smearing that is
                  caused by the correlation between the lensing
                  kernels at different redshifts. Lensing clusters
                  with lower mass limits of $10^{14.0}$ $h^{-1}$
                  \solarmassbib, $10^{14.7}$ $h^{-1}$ \solarmassbib,
                  $10^{15.0}$ $h^{-1}$ \solarmassbib can be detected with
